FOODBORNE DISEASE INCIDENCE DECREASING - USA (02)
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Foodborne disease incidence decreasing - USA 980525214838
Date: Tue, 26 May 1998 11:10:46 CDT
From: "Valerie Deneen" <deneev1@mdh-dpc.health.state.mn.us>

U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman is correct that, at this point, we
can not extrapolate from data gathered in five FoodNet sites to the nation.
What's more, it is not clear to me that data from a handful of sites can be
generalized to the country next year or at any time.
Not only does the distribution of pathogens vary geographically, but
surveillance and the capacity for investigating and confirming foodborne
disease outbreaks varies across state and local health departments.
Furthermore, it is likely that most cases and outbreaks of foodborne
illness are caused by gastrointestinal viruses, probably spread by infected
food workers. The surveillance system for reporting cases of foodborne
disease emphasizes bacterial pathogens and does not include
gastrointestinal viruses. And even the outbreak reporting system is
unlikely to capture outbreaks of viral etiology despite recent developments
in laboratory detection. This has significant implications if surveillance
data are used to inform public health policy decisions. Limiting the
transmission of bacterial pathogens from farm animals to table is
important, but should not overshadow viral pathogens and the role of
infected food workers in transmitting disease.
FoodNet activities will help to improve foodborne disease surveillance in
the United States and better define risk factors for foodborne illness
caused by bacterial pathogens. However, as we begin to analyse these data,
we should be conservative in drawing a national picture of foodborne
illness from them.
--
Valerie Deneen
Acute Disease Epidemiology
Minnesota Department of Health
(612) 623-5414
(612) 623-5730 fax
