[2
Date: Tue, 26 May 1998 06:48:42 +0100
From: Oz <Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk>

>>According to a report released Friday based on data collected by the
Centers for Disease Control (CDC) and cited here, the estimated rate of
food-borne disease fell slightly last year to about 50 cases for every
100,000 Americans, but government scientists are still far from certain how
many people get sick from bad food.<<
A comment is surely in order here. This rate is one clinical case per
person every 20 years. This is impressively low considering that around
1,000 meals are consumed per person annually.
The quoted death rate of 9000 people (presumably in the US with a
population of about 250M) is 4 per 100,000. A mortality [CFR of nearly 10%
seems to me to be very high (and rather puzzling) and presumably is being
examined rather more closely. I wonder how many of these stem from
immunosuppressed people or 'public' functions where relatively large
numbers are affected from one source.
--
O. Hotz de Baar
UK
e-mail: Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk
